subSubSection.paragraph:
Head ( Figs 2–10 ). Antennae longer than body length, with 1.56 mm in holotype (
Figs 1 – 3
). Antennal segments ratio of Ant I:II:III:IV as 1:1.61:3.26:11.50. Ant IV with 27 subsegments on males and 28 on females, subsegment 1 with 10 chaetae, subsegments 2–3 with 6 and 7 chaetae respectively, subsegments 4–6 with 9 chaetae each, subsegments 7–27(26 on males) with 10 chaetae each, subsegment 28(27 on males) with about 25 chaetae, one apical curved ( Fig. 2 ). Ant III with 20 chaetae, four longer and thicker on basal half, apical organ typical with two sense rods inside two separate invaginations, surrounding subapical microsensillum present ( Fig. 3 ). Ant II with 16 chaetae, four longer and thicker ( Fig. 3 ). Ant I with five thick chaetae plus one smaller ( Fig. 3 ). Head length (eyes to mouth) of holotype 0.68 mm . Eyes 8+8, lenses subequal in size ( Fig. 4 ). Clypeal area a–g lines with 7/7/6/5(+1)/ 6(+1)/7/3 chaetae respectively, three central pairs of longer chaetae in lines d , e and f respectively, four extra chaetae with unclear homologies (circled) ( Figs 4–5 ). Interantennal area with α and γ lines with 2 and 1 chaetae respectively, γ chaeta longer than others; frontal area with A–E lines with 1(+1)/2/2(+1)/2(+1)/2 chaetae respectively; 1, 1, 2 and 1 spiniform chaetae in lines B , C , D and E respectively ( Fig. 4 ). Ventral head chaetotaxy as in Fig. 5 , ventral groove with 2 surrounding chaetae, four anterior post-labial chaetae; labial basomedian field with four chaetae, one of them longer, basolateral field with five chaetae, proximal one smaller. Maxillary outer lobe with basal chaeta smaller than apical, both smooth; sublobal plate partially subdivided, lacking chaeta-like appendages ( Fig. 6 ). Labial palp papillae as in Fig. 7 with five proximal chaetae, formula of guard chaetae of each papilla as: H (2), A (0), B (5), C (0), D (4), E (3) + blunt lateral process not reaching papilla E base. Labral chaetotaxy with 3 pl, 2(+1) p , 2(+1) m and 2 a chaetae, p2 larger than others, a1 longer than a2 ; labrum with four labial crests ( Fig. 8 ), with four pointed papillae. Maxillae typical, with six lamellae, the three internal serrated ( Fig. 9 ). Mandibles with 5–6 incisive apical teeth ( Fig. 10 ).

